  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Ensuring safe and uninterrupted access between IDP sites and main cities in Northwest Syria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed intervention aims to contribute to the improved living conditions and resilience of conflict-affected households in Northwest Syria by enhancing access to basic services, main markets and livelihood opportunities. To achieve this objective, ACTED will conduct the rehabilitation of some of the main access roads serving camp clusters in Idleb and Northern Aleppo governorates. This will ensure that both IDPs residing in the camps and humanitarian agencies can access the camps in a safe and uninterrupted manner. The rehabilitation of the roads will notably improve the implementation of ACTED&#x2019;s activities in camps such as the provision of water trucking, food and winterization activities. Additionally, the targeted roads will also contribute to improve market linkages between IDP sites, host communities and main markets, in order to facilitate greater market functionality and reduce dependence to in-kind assistance.

The road rehabilitation will be combined with the provision of income-generating opportunities to 225 vulnerable households residing in camps and settlements in Idleb and Northern Aleppo governorates. These households will support the rehabilitation of the roads, including drainage and road paving and asphalting. 

Overall, this project will support 122,388 IDPs and host community members (approximately 20,398 households) through the rehabilitation of 9 roads serving Kherbet-Aljowz and Qah camps areas in Idleb governorate and 7 camps in Aleppo governorate (A&#x2019;zaz district). In addition, 225 vulnerable households will access income-generating opportunities through cash for work opportunities. This intervention will also complement ACTED&#x2019;s intervention in Kaj area under alternative funding, by enhancing market linkages between the Kaj area and larger markets in nearby cities, for small and medium businesses supported through cash grants.</narrative>
  </description>
